Because sc is like scanning tokens. Wait, in Java code:

They do:

int N = Integer.parseInt(sc.next());
int K = Integer.parseInt(sc.next());
String S = sc.next();

So the next() is the next token. So the inputs would be, for example, something like:

5 1
RLRLR

Then sc.next() first reads '5', then next() gives '1', then next() gives 'RLRLR'. So in the input, the string S is provided as a single token. So even if it's given on one line with everything, the third sc.next() would pick the string correctly. So in Fortran, perhaps we'll need to read after the N and K, then read the string in a line. But in Fortran, the way to do that would be to read everything until end of line.

